Deputy President William Ruto. 
Photo credit: File | Sila Kiplagat | Nation Media Group

 

Among those that contributed was Kieni MP Kanini Kega and the local Constituency Development Fund (CDF) chairman James Munene who gave Sh5,000 each. 

But the noble gesture is now causing a stir after Mr Kihenjo was allegedly asked to return the money for questioning development projects in Kieni. 

The altercation took place in a WhatsApp group of which Mr Kihenjo, Mr Kega and Mr Munene are members. 














Kega, man spar over Sh5,000 wedding contribution



window.hasEmbeddedVideo = true;
 

Mr Kega had asked the Deputy President Dr William Ruto to resign from the Jubilee Party so that he could popularise the United Democratic Alliance (UDA), a party linked to him ahead of the 2022 General Election. 






"As a diehard supporter of the Deputy President, I commented that the MP should be the first to resign as he recently joined Kanu," Mr Kihenjo narrated, insisting that his comment came after the MP hosted Kanu leader Gideon Moi in Mweiga within the Kieni Constituency last month. 

Monies donated 

His comment, he says, attracted the wrath of the CDF chairman who asked for a refund of the monies donated towards his wedding. 

"This was the fourth time this was happening and I couldn't take it anymore," Mr Kihenjo, who was later ejected from the group, said. 

The Kieni MP belongs to the Kieleweke wing of the Jubilee Party that supports President Uhuru Kenyatta and the Handshake with ODM leader Raila Odinga. 



