The 36-year-old survey assistant said the day after he was asked to refund the money, he rallied his friends and they raised the Sh10,000 and refunded the MP and the CDF chairman. 

Besides speaking in support of the DP, Mr Kihenjo says he also had questioned why a Sh10 million Naromoru water project had taken long to be completed. 

"I did not want further embarrassments and I wanted peace of mind. Furthermore, he should have been a cheerful giver and taken criticism kindly," he said. 

But contacted for a comment, Mr Kega denied having asked for the refund, saying he contributed the money as he does to dozens of other fundraisers to help the needy. 






Kanu party Chairman Gideon Moi during a Building Bridges Initiative consultative meeting in Iten, Elgeyo Marakwet County, on December 5, 2020. 
Photo credit: Jared Nyataya | Nation Media Group

 

He said he contributes more than Sh500,000 a month. 

"I contribute to needy cases monthly and when someone refunds your money, it means he was not needy as such," he said. 

He further accused Mr Kihenjo of politicising the issue, “which is immaterial" noting that he (Mr Kihenjo) was being pressurised by his political opponents. 

"This is not about development but a machination by people from the other side and it is happening because of my political stand and I won't change it," he said. 

